* {{cite web|title=Bundesverwaltungsgericht lehnt Klagen gegen BND teilweise ab|url=https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Bundesverwaltungsgericht-lehnt-Klagen-gegen-BND-teilweise-ab-3570480.html|publisher=heise online|accessdate=2 January 2017|language=de-DE}}
* {{cite web|last1=Reinsch|first1=Melanie|title=Massenüberwachung: Journalistenorganisation verklagt BND|url=http://www.berliner-zeitung.de/politik/massenueberwachung-journalistenorganisation-verklagt-bnd-25293082|publisher=Berliner Zeitung|accessdate=2 January 2017|language=de-DE}}
* {{cite web|title=UN Says Mass Surveillance Violates Human Rights|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20141015/07353028836/un-says-mass-surveillance-violates-human-rights.shtml|publisher=Techdirt|accessdate=2 January 2017}}
* {{cite web|title=Does government spying violate human rights law? - Right Now|url=http://rightnow.org.au/opinion-3/does-government-spying-violate-human-rights-law/|publisher=Right Now|accessdate=2 January 2017|date=11 March 2014}}
</ref> and of failing to pursue security effectively.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hadjimatheou|first1=Katerina|title=The Relative Moral Risks of Untargeted and Targeted Surveillance|journal=Ethical Theory and Moral Practice|date=1 January 2014|volume=17|issue=2|pages=187–207|url=https://philpapers.org/rec/HADTRM|accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref>

A 2014 report to the [[UN General Assembly]] by the [[United Nations]]' top official for [[counter-terrorism]] and [[human rights]] condemned mass electronic surveillance as a clear violation of core [[privacy]] rights guaranteed by multiple treaties and conventions and makes a distinction between "targeted surveillance" - which "depend[s] upon the existence of prior suspicion of the targeted individual or organization" — and "mass surveillance", by which "states with high levels of [[Internet]] penetration can [...] gain access to the telephone and e-mail content of an effectively unlimited number of users and maintain an overview of Internet activity associated with particular [[website]]s".<ref name=theintercept1>{{cite web|last1=Greenwald|first1=Glenn|title=UN Report Finds Mass Surveillance Violates International Treaties and Privacy Rights|url=https://theintercept.com/2014/10/15/un-investigator-report-condemns-mass-surveillance/|publisher=The Intercept|accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref>

The United Kingdom's [[House of Lords]] also distinguishes between these two broad types of surveillance:<ref>{{cite web|title=Surveillance: Citizens and the State - Constitution Committee|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200809/ldselect/ldconst/18/1804.htm|publisher=House of Lords|accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref>

<blockquote>
* Mass surveillance is also known as “passive” or “undirected” surveillance. [...] It is not targeted on any particular individual but gathers images and information for possible future use. CCTV and databases are examples of mass surveillance.
* Targeted surveillance is surveillance directed at particular individuals and can involve the use of specific powers by authorised public agencies. Targeted surveillance can be carried out overtly or covertly, and can involve human agents. Under the [[Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000]] (RIPA), targeted covert surveillance is “directed” if it is carried out for a specific investigation or operation. By comparison, if it is carried out on designated premises or on a vehicle, it is “intrusive” surveillance. Targeting methods include the interception of communications, the use of communications “traffic” data, visual surveillance devices, and devices that sense movement, objects or persons.
</blockquote>

Only targeted interception of traffic and location data in order to combat serious crime, including [[terrorism]], is justified, according to a decision by the [[European Court of Justice]].<ref name=theguardian1/><ref>{{cite web|title=European court’s snooping judgment ‘bolsters privilege’|url=https://www.lawgazette.co.uk/law/european-courts-snooping-judgment-bolsters-privilege/5059203.article|publisher=Law Society Gazette|accessdate=3 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bowcott|first1=Owen|title=EU's highest court delivers blow to UK snooper's charter|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2016/dec/21/eus-highest-court-delivers-blow-to-uk-snoopers-charter|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=3 January 2017|date=21 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Heathman|first1=Amelia|title=EU court deals major blow to UK's controversial snooper's charter|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/eu-rules-against-snoopers-charter|publisher=WIRED UK|accessdate=3 January 2017}}</ref>

