== Selection of targets ==
{{Expand section|date=January 2017}}
The current approach of the [[NSA]] and its related organizations is attempting to collect all [[SIGINT|signals]] of everybody at all times without any prior selection.<ref>{{cite web|title=The crux of the NSA story in one phrase: 'collect it all'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/15/crux-nsa-collect-it-all|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=4 January 2017|date=15 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Maass|first1=Peter|title=Inside NSA, Officials Privately Criticize "Collect It All" Surveillance|url=https://theintercept.com/2015/05/28/nsa-officials-privately-criticize-collect-it-all-surveillance/|publisher=The Intercept|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cole|first1=David|title=‘No Place to Hide’ by Glenn Greenwald, on the NSA’s sweeping efforts to ‘Know it All’|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/no-place-to-hide-by-glenn-greenwald-on-the-nsas-sweeping-efforts-to-know-it-all/2014/05/12/dfa45dee-d628-11e3-8a78-8fe50322a72c_story.html|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=4 January 2017|date=12 May 2014}}</ref> So any current selection is only used for targets of special interest, human review or special resource allocation.

Such selectors include searching the web for the [[Privacy software|privacy-enhancing software tools]] such as [[Tor (anonymity network)|Tor]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zetter|first1=Kim|title=The NSA Is Targeting Users of Privacy Services, Leaked Code Shows|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/07/nsa-targets-users-of-privacy-services/|publisher=WIRED|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NSA targets the privacy-conscious|url=https://daserste.ndr.de/panorama/aktuell/nsa230_page-1.html|publisher=Das Erste|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref>

A leaked document revealed that for the [[XKeyscore]] program using language out of place for the region one is in, using encryption and searching the web for 'suspicious stuff' were suggested as selectors.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leyden|first1=John|title=New NSA tool exposed: XKeyscore sees 'nearly EVERYTHING you do online'|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/07/31/prism_put_in_the_shade_by_leak_about_even_more_powerful_snoop_tool/|publisher=The Register|accessdate=8 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gallagher|first1=Ryan|title=NSA Targets Internet Users Who Search for "Suspicious Stuff," Newly Revealed Documents Show|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2013/07/31/xkeyscore_nsa_targets_internet_users_who_search_for_suspicious_stuff.html|publisher=Slate|accessdate=8 January 2017|date=31 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=XKeyscore presentation from 2008 – read in full|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/interactive/2013/jul/31/nsa-xkeyscore-program-full-presentation|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=8 January 2017|date=31 July 2013}}</ref>

=== Societal control and consent ===
Selectors for who to surveil and for what to look for in searches for unknown threats as well as their extents can be decided upon by society. Verifiable public consent on broad selectors and their extents as well as proper mechanisms and institutions for oversight may allow for a better cooperation of private sectors and citizens with their intelligence communities.

=== Germany and NSA's selector lists ===
In [[Operation Eikonal]] German [[Federal Intelligence Service (Germany)|BND]] agents received "Selector Lists" − search terms for their [[Dragnet (policing)|dragnet surveillance]]. They contain IP addresses, mobile phone numbers and email accounts with the BND surveillance system containing hundreds of thousands and possibly more than a million such targets.<ref name=spiegel1>{{cite web|title=Spying Close to Home: German Intelligence Under Fire for NSA Cooperation - SPIEGEL ONLINE - International|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/german-intelligence-agency-bnd-under-fire-for-nsa-cooperation-a-1030593.html|publisher=SPIEGEL ONLINE|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref> These lists have been subject of controversy as in 2008 it was revealed that they contained some terms targeting the [[European Aeronautic Defence and Space Company]] (EADS), the [[Eurocopter]] project<ref name="ts1">{{cite web|url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/bnd-und-nsa-die-chronologie-des-spionageskandals/11722810.html|title=BND und NSA: Die Chronologie des Spionageskandals – Politik – Tagesspiegel|work=tagesspiegel.de|language=German}}</ref> as well as French administration,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/die-neue-bnd-affaere-ein-foul-mit-folgen-1.2448810|title=Wie die NSA europäische Unternehmen ausspionierte|work=Süddeutsche.de|language=German}}</ref><ref name=spiegel1/> which were first noticed by BND employees in 2005.<ref name="ts1" /> Other selectors were found to target the administration of Austria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/inland/nsa-spitzelei-bnd-soll-12-000-suchbegriffe-geloescht-haben-13569002.html|title=NSA-Spitzelei: BND soll 12.000 Suchbegriffe gelöscht haben|publisher=Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung GmbH|date=1 May 2015|language=German}}</ref> After the revelations made by whistleblower Edward Snowden the BND decided to investigate the issue whose October 2013 conclusion was that at least 2,000 of these selectors were aimed at Western European or even German interests which has been a violation of the Memorandum of Agreement that the US and Germany signed in 2002 in the wake of the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 terror attacks]].<ref name=spiegel1/> After reports emerged in 2014 that EADS and Eurocopter had been surveillance targets the [[The Left (Germany)|Left Party]] and the [[Greens (Germany)|Greens]] filed an official request to obtain evidence of the violations.<ref name=spiegel1/><ref>{{cite web|title=Bundesverfassungsgericht - BVerfG, Beschluss des Zweiten Senats vom 13. n|url=https://www.bundesverfassungsgericht.de/SharedDocs/Entscheidungen/DE/2016/10/es20161013_2bve000215.html|website=bundesverfassungsgericht.de|accessdate=4 January 2017|language=de|date=13 October 2016}}</ref>

The BND's project group charged with supporting the [[German Parliamentary Committee investigating the NSA spying scandal|NSA investigative committee in German parliament]] set up in spring 2014, reviewed the selectors and discovered 40,000 suspicious search parameters, including espionage targets in Western European governments and numerous companies. The group also confirmed suspicions that the NSA had systematically violated German interests and concluded that the Americans could have perpetrated [[economic espionage]] directly under the Germans' noses.<ref name=spiegel1/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Denkler|first1=Thorsten|title=Geheimdienst-Affäre: NSA jubelte BND deutsche Spähziele unter|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/geheimdienst-affaere-nsa-jubelte-bnd-deutsche-spaehziele-unter-1.2715253|publisher=Süddeutsche Zeitung|accessdate=4 January 2017|language=de}}</ref> The investigative parliamentary committee was not granted access to the NSA's selectors list as an appeal led by opposition politicians failed at Germany's top court - instead the ruling coalition appointed an administrative judge, [[Kurt Graulich]], as a "person of trust" who was granted access to the list and briefed the investigative commission on its contents after analyzing the 40,000 parameters.<ref>{{cite web|title=German Constitutional Court rules out access to NSA's 'selectors' list|url=http://www.dw.com/en/german-constitutional-court-rules-out-access-to-nsas-selectors-list/a-36396385|publisher=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Designierter NSA-Sonderermittler: Ein Mann, 40.000 brisante Daten|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/nsa-sonderermittler-kurt-graulich-ein-mann-40-000-datensaetze-a-1040661.html|publisher=SPIEGEL ONLINE|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref> In his almost 300-paged report<ref>{{cite web|title=Der Graulich-Abschlussbericht|url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/graulich-abschlussbericht-101.pdf|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref> Graulich concluded that European government agencies were targeted massively and that Americans hence broke contractual agreements. He also found that German targets which received special protection from surveillance of domestic intelligence agencies by [[Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany|Germany's Basic Law (Grundgesetz)]] − including numerous enterprises based in Germany − were featured in the NSA's wishlist in a surprising plenitude.<ref>{{cite web|title=Geheimdienstaffäre: Sonderermittler spricht von klarem Vertragsbruch der NSA|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/nsa-selektorenliste-kurt-graulich-spricht-von-klarem-vertragsbruch-a-1060280.html|publisher=SPIEGEL ONLINE|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref> While the magnitude differs there have also been problematic BND-internal selectors which have been used until end of 2013 - around two thirds of 3300 targets were related to EU and NATO states.<ref>{{cite web|title=Geheimdienstkontrolleure: BND hat gegen Recht und Auftrag verstoßen|url=https://www.heise.de/newsticker/meldung/Geheimdienstkontrolleure-BND-hat-gegen-Recht-und-Auftrag-verstossen-3045627.html|publisher=Heise Online|accessdate=4 January 2017|language=de-DE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=BND hat jahrelang unter Freunden spioniert|url=http://www.dw.com/de/bnd-hat-jahrelang-unter-freunden-spioniert/a-19393446|publisher=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Decker|first1=Markus|title=Geheimdienst-Affäre: BND spitzelte mit eigenen Selektoren|url=http://www.fr-online.de/datenschutz/geheimdienst-affaere-bnd-spitzelte-mit-eigenen-selektoren,1472644,32163156.html|publisher=Frankfurter Rundschau|accessdate=4 January 2017|language=de}}</ref> [[Klaus Landefeld]], member of the board at the Internet industry association [[Eco International]], has met intelligence officials and legislators to present suggestions for improvement, like streamlining the selector system.<ref name="aljazeera1">{{cite web|last1=Somaskanda|first1=Sumi|title=Is Big Brother coming to Germany?|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2016/12/big-brother-coming-germany-161213062129779.html|publisher=Al Jazeera|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref>
