{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox official post |post = Ambassador-at-Large |body = the United States for International Religious Freedom |nativename = |insignia = US Department of State official seal.svg |insigniasize = 120 |insigniacaption = Seal of the United States Department of State |department = |image = Sam Brownback official photo.jpg |alt = |incumbent = [[Sam Brownback]] |incumbentsince = February 1, 2018 |style = |residence = |appointer = The [[President of the United States|President]] |appointer_qualified = {{nowrap|{{small|with the [[advice and consent]] of the [[United States Senate|Senate]]}}}} |appointerpost = |termlength = |inaugural = [[Robert A. Seiple]] |formation = 1999 |last = |abolished = |succession = |deputy = |salary = |website = [https://www.state.gov/g/drl/irf/ U.S. Office - IRF] }}
The '''United States Ambassador-at-Large for International Religious Freedom''' is the [[ambassador-at-large]] who heads the [[Office of International Religious Freedom]] in the [[United States Department of State|U.S. Department of State]].
The position was created by the [[International Religious Freedom Act of 1998]]. The first ambassador-at-large was [[Bob Seiple]]<ref>[https://www.state.gov/www/about_state/biography/seiple.html U.S. Department of State. "Biography Robert A Seiple." September 11, 2009.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712101613/http://www.state.gov/www/about_state/biography/seiple.html |date=July 12, 2011 }}</ref> who served from 1999 to 2001. He was succeeded by [[John Hanford]]<ref>[https://www.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/113758.htm U.S. Department of State. "Biography John V. Hanford III." September 11, 2009.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090313073030/http://www.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/113758.htm |date=March 13, 2009 }}</ref> who served from May 2002 until January 2009. [[Suzan Johnson Cook]] served in the role from May 2011 to October 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/religious-liberty-ambassadors-resignation-raises-concerns/|title=Religious liberty ambassador's resignation raises concerns |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140402070646/http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/religious-liberty-ambassadors-resignation-raises-concerns/|archivedate=April 2, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 28, 2014, President [[Barack Obama]] nominated [[David Saperstein (rabbi)|Rabbi David Saperstein]] for the position. On December 15, 2014 the [[United States Senate|Senate]] [[United States congressional hearing#Confirmation hearings|confirmed]] him to the office, making him the first non-Christian to hold this post.<ref name="time">Dias, Elizabeth. [http://time.com/3046464/religious-freedom-rabbi-david-saperstein/ "Obama Nominates Rabbi to Religious Freedom Post"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150117212709/http://time.com/3046464/religious-freedom-rabbi-david-saperstein/ |date=January 17, 2015 }}, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', July 28, 2014. Retrieved July 31, 2014.</ref><ref name="AL">Campbell, Kay. [http://www.al.com/living/index.ssf/2014/12/rabbi_saperstein_confirmed.html "Rabbi David Saperstein confirmed as U.S. Ambassador for Religious Freedom"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219034314/http://www.al.com/living/index.ssf/2014/12/rabbi_saperstein_confirmed.html |date=December 19, 2014 }}, AL.com, December 17, 2014. Retrieved December 19, 2014.</ref><ref name="timesofisrael">[http://www.timesofisrael.com/us-senate-approves-rabbi-as-freedom-of-faith-envoy/ "US Senate approves rabbi as freedom of faith envoy"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403054018/http://www.timesofisrael.com/us-senate-approves-rabbi-as-freedom-of-faith-envoy/ |date=April 3, 2015 }}, ''[[The Times of Israel]]'', December 15, 2014. Retrieved December 15, 2014.</ref>
On July 26, 2017, the [[White House]] announced the nomination of [[Sam Brownback]], then-[[Governor of Kansas]] to fill the vacancy in the office.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=890359611429183488|title=BREAKING: White House: Trump to nominate Kansas Gov. Sam Brownback as ambassador at large for international religious freedom.|date=July 26, 2017|user=AP|access-date=July 27, 2017 |publisher=Associated Press}}</ref> Five months later, the Senate had yet to hold a confirmation vote, so per Senate rules, he was required to be nominated again in 2018 in order for a vote to be held.<ref>[http://www2.ljworld.com/news/2017/dec/22/brownbacks-nomination-set-return-white-house/ Brownback’s nomination for ambassador post not carried over, will return to White House], Lawrence ''[[Journal World]]'', December 22, 2017. Retrieved December 27, 2017.</ref> He was confirmed to the position on January 24, 2018, on a 49-49 vote of the Senate, with Vice President [[Mike Pence]] breaking the tie in favor of Brownback.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=2&vote=00022|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 115th Congress - 2nd Session|website=www.senate.gov|access-date=2018-01-24}}</ref>
